<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Rivals gather to woo the UK's dairy farmers: Guy de
Jonquieres on ventures being formed to take over from the Milk Marketing
Board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For 60 years, Britain's 30,000 dairy farmers have been sheltered from harsh
commercial realities by the monopoly purchasing umbrella of the Milk
Marketing Board (MMB). Now they are being wooed by the very organisations
from which the MMB was originally set up to protect them - the big dairies
and food processors.
With about 18 months to go until the MMB's statutory monopoly is abolished,
large milk users across the country are competing to line up secure supplies
once producers become free to sell to whomever they choose.
The most striking initiative was launched yesterday by Northern Foods, the
country's largest private-sector dairy group, which hopes in the next year
to persuade between 5,000 and 6,000 English and Welsh farmers to join it in
a planned co-operative venture, the Northern Milk Partnership.
The non-profit venture would supply exclusively the 2bn litres of milk,
worth Pounds 500m, which Northern buys annually for its liquid milk sales
and food-manufacturing businesses.
Though no other large users appear to be planning similar arrangements,
several are seeking to interest farmers in supplying them direct from next
year. They include the UK subsidiary of Nestle, the Swiss food group, the
Danish-owned MD Foods (formerly Associated Dairies) and the Co-operative
Wholesale Society.
The MMB, meanwhile, is urging farmers to remain loyal after its planned
re-birth as a voluntary co-operative trading under the name Milk Marque. It
hopes to supply 80 per cent of the Pounds 3bn annual milk market, a share
some observers believe it would have to achieve to cover its high costs.
Northern's initiative is widely seen as a pre-emptive strike to limit Milk
Marque's market power. The venture would account initially for 17 per cent
of the total UK milk market and aims for as much as 25 per cent in the
longer run. However, it faces a number of uncertainties.
The biggest hurdle is overcoming farmers' traditional mistrust of bigger
customers. The partnership has scored a minor public relations coup by
naming as its chairman Mr Richard Smith, a bluff Yorkshire dairy farmer with
120 cows, who resigned as an MMB director last year because he disagreed
with the Milk Marque Scheme.
To woo producers, Northern Foods is offering to buy all its needs from the
partnership's members at prices higher than those paid by Milk Marque. The
company would negotiate its contract collectively with producer
representatives and guarantee farmers regularly monthly payments.
Mr Christopher Haskins, Northern Foods' chairman, says the project is 'a
totally new concept of co-operation'. By bridging the gap between producers
and marketers, he believes it could serve as a model in other parts of
agriculture at a time when the government is seeking ways to reduce
Britain's food trade deficit of more than Pounds 5bn a year.
Mr Haskins believes the venture will prosper economically by cutting out the
MMB's bureaucracy and costs. It will have a permanent staff of only 25, to
be housed in Northern Foods' Hull headquarters, compared with the 560
employed at the MMB's head office.
The partnership will concentrate on recruiting farmers close to Northern
Foods' network of dairies. The company will transport milk directly from the
farm gate, instead of relying on the MMB to collect supplies, often from
remote parts of the country, and store them at central depots.
Northern has a reputation as a highly efficient operator, both in liquid
milk delivery and in its food-manufacturing businesses, which are leading
suppliers to Marks and Spencer. The group has stripped huge costs out of
Express Dairies since it was acquired from Grand Metropolitan last year.
However, competition is expected to reduce Northern Foods' cost advantage by
making rivals more efficient. The MMB has already announced plans to shed 60
per cent of its head office staff and is expected to restructure its charges
for milk collection to benefit farms close to dairies.
Though Northern Foods has historically paid producers about 1p per litre
more than the national average for milk, that premium may be harder to
sustain in a liberalised market. Some observers believe the desire to keep
producers loyal to the planned partnership could lead it to over-pay in the
future. That, in turn, could push up prices across the market.
On the other hand, if the venture succeeds as well as Northern Foods hopes,
some analysts think the group could face pressure from milk producers for a
share of corporate profits - and even for a direct stake in its dairy and
processing operations.
With so many uncertainties looming, other dairy groups seem likely to
hesitate before committing themselves to following Northern Foods' example.
Unigate, for instance, says that once the MMB monopoly ends it will buy milk
through whichever channel the producers favour.
MMB, meanwhile, was out to minimise the scale of the Northern Foods
challenge.
'It's not unexpected,' Mr Andrew Dare, chief executive, said yesterday. 'But
I have heard nothing that would make the planned venture more attractive
than Milk Marque. Our role in life is clear: we're there to represent
farmers. Who will represent farmers in the Northern Foods set-up?'
