<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Israel to take back 100 deportees: Pressure from US prompts
reversal of policy on stranded Palestinians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL announced last night it would take back 100 of the more than 400
Palestinians it expelled to Lebanon in December and halve the term of exile
for the remainder in a dramatic reversal of policy prompted by intense
pressure from the US.
The 396 deportees still stranded in south Lebanon, all alleged Islamic
fundamentalist militants from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, said
before the decision they would not accept any solution except full
compliance with United Nations Security Council resolution 799 calling for
the immediate return of all those expelled.
But Mr Yitzhak Rabin, the Israeli prime minister, made clear the concessions
were part of what he called 'a package deal' which would ensure that the US
blocked any further action against Israel in the Council over the issue.
Mr Rabin, who until yesterday publicly refused to back down on the
deportations, said Washington had also agreed to press all parties to resume
the Middle East peace talks. The Palestine Liberation Organisation had
previously said it would not return to talks until the deportees went home.
After a special cabinet meeting in Jerusalem, Mr Rabin described the
initiative as a difficult step for the government. It originally ordered the
unprecedented expulsions to strike against Hamas, a powerful Islamic group
in the West Bank and Gaza, and the smaller Islamic Jihad group which had
both carried out a series of killings of Israeli soldiers. But the
deportations incurred overwhelming international condemnation.
'We had to face the international community, with the reality of a new
administration in the US which I believe is friendly towards Israel and we
had to create with it an infrastructure of understanding which would enable
us in the next four years to exhaust the opportunity of peacemaking,' Mr
Rabin said.
The Clinton administration had pressed hard for concessions since the
Israeli High Court approved the expulsions last week. The US wanted to avoid
a confrontation at the UN and to preserve the fragile peace process. Last
night at the UN in New York Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state,
said the move made further action on the matter by the Council unnecessary
and even counter-productive.
Mr Rabin said the returning deportees would be brought back within a few
days 'to their previous status' - a return to jail for most. The rest would
remain exiled for one year instead of two. Israel would also provide them
with humanitarian aid.
The EC last night welcomed the Israeli cabinet's compromise as a 'very good
step' which would help to put Middle East peace talks back on track, Lionel
Barber adds in Brussels.
But Mr Niels Helvig Petersen, Danish foreign minister, declined to offer
total endorsement of the plan or indicate whether it would lead to a speedy
resumption of talks to update the 1975 Israeli-EC trade agreement.
</TEXT>
