<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / International Company News: Cominco deficit widens to
CDollars 95m in final period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMINCO, the Canadian metals and fertiliser group, suffered a heavy
fourth-quarter loss as a result of soft metal prices and the decision to
write off a third of the cost of its troubled lead smelter at Trail, British
Columbia.
The loss, including the CDollars 50m (USDollars 39.2m) smelter write-down,
was CDollars 95.2m, or CDollars 1.21 a share, against a CDollars 16.3m loss,
or 21 cents, a year earlier. Revenues rose to CDollars 364.6m from CDollars
344m.
The loss for the year narrowed to CDollars 30.2m from CDollars 41.3m, thanks
largely to a gain earlier in the year from the sale of a 46 per cent
interest in Aberfoyle, the Australian mining group.
Cominco's mining and metals business swung to a fourth-quarter operating
loss of CDollars 40.5m from a CDollars 5.5m profit a year earlier, due
largely to an after-tax charge of CDollars 30m to reflect the impact of
lower metal prices on zinc and ferro-nickel inventories.
Canadian Pacific Forest Products, the newsprint producer, suffered a net
loss of CDollars 59.5m or CDollars 1.13 a share in the fourth quarter,
compared with a loss of CDollars 96m or CDollars 2.19 a year earlier, writes
Robert Gibbens in Montreal.
The company, controlled by Canadian Pacific, had sales of CDollars 467m,
against CDollars 481m. The fall was mainly due to a mill shutdown and asset
sales.
For all 1992 the loss was CDollars 248m or CDollars 4.82 a share, against a
deficit of CDollars 571m or CDollars 13 in 1991.
</TEXT>
