<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Eurobond debt issuance at a record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INCREASED borrowing by European governments boosted the amount of new debt
issued in the Eurobond market to a record Dollars 35.7bn (Pounds 23.6bn) in
January.
The US corporate debt market also had its busiest month ever, with a total
of Dollars 36.9bn, made up largely of refinancings, according to figures
from Securities Data.
While most European governments have finished replenishing their currency
reserves after last autumn's foreign exchange debacle, they still face
mounting budget deficits.
Sovereign borrowers accounted for more than Dollars 8bn of total Eurobond
issues in January, as their increased funding needs forced them to seek
funds outside their domestic bond markets. Volume the previous January
totalled Dollars 34.7bn, of which less than Dollars 5bn was made up of
government debt, according to IFR Securities Data.
'European countries are under pressure to bring down debt levels to meet
criteria for European monetary union, but with weaker economic growth and a
shrinking tax base, this is not going to be an easy task,' said Mr Jim
Pelgrift, executive director of Morgan Stanley International.
The slowdown in most of the world's economies and the prospect of low
inflation is likely to provide favourable conditions for bond markets.
'Every market one looks at, there is potential for a rally,' according to Mr
Tom Skwarek, managing director of capial markets at JP Morgan.
The economic slowdown has discouraged European companies from tapping the
market, since they do not need to borrow to invest. In the US, companies
have been taking advantage of lower interest rates to lock in fixed-rate
financing, as the economy emerges from recession. Volume in January just
topped last January's Dollars 36.9bn record.
International bonds, Page 21
