<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is a particularly meaty Monday night for documentaries, but for plenty
of viewers the pick of the bunch may be World in Action's Don't Bank on Us
(ITV, 8.30), an investigation into the abrupt decline in reputation
experienced by Britain's banks. The programme, postponed from last week,
examines allegations of over-charging.
Looking beyond such parochial concerns, there is the first of a two-part
Panorama, The Bitter-Enders (BBC 1, 9.30), in which David Dimbleby looks
deep into the heart of South Africa's tragic and seemingly unstoppable
violence. 'Bitter-enders', it appears, were the Afrikaners who turned their
backs on peace at the close of the Boer War.
Horizon; No Ordinary Genius (BBC 2, 8.00) concludes its portrait of the
prodigiously talented physicist, Richard Feynman.
Earlier, a well-made and enthralling series returns to the screen, A Secret
World of Sex (BBC 2, 7.30). Tonight's episode is a reminder of a time, not
long ago, when for a woman to have a child out of wedlock could be
interpreted as deviation bordering on lunacy.
</TEXT>
