<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Industrialists back Maastricht, says poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A POLL indicates that 75 per cent of British industry and local authorities
would vote in favour of the Maastricht treaty if the UK held a referendum,
Gary Mead writes.
But it also shows that 37 per cent believe they receive unfair treatment
from Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, and his
office.
The poll was conducted by the UK-based political consultancy Decision Makers
among the UK's top 1,000 companies and 500 local authorities as well as the
top 1,000 companies elsewhere in the EC and in the Efta group of nations.
Among all types of the UK respondents, 59 per cent said they favoured
staying outside the European exchange rate mechanism until a closer and more
stable alignment of currencies was achieved. The survey indicated that only
26 per cent of UK industry believes it receives fair treatment from Brussels
Attitudes of UK Local Authorities and the top 2,000 EC companies. Decision
Makers, Premier House, 20 Gladstone Street, London SE1 6E1. Pounds 25.
