<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Secondary school class sizes increase sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLASS sizes have increased sharply in secondary schools in England's cities
despite government claims to have improved the pupil-teacher ratio, research
by Oxford Brookes University has found.
The research by the university (formerly Oxford Polytechnic) based on recent
Department for Education figures, shows that in 48 metropolitan local
education authorities (LEAs) the pupil-to-teacher ratio at secondary level
worsened by 0.5 or more pupils per teacher between January 1989 and January
1992.
In only seven metropolitan LEAs has the ratio remained steady. In not one
has it improved by more than 0.5.
In some inner-city areas, the deterioration in the three years completely
wiped out the gains of the previous 15 years. In Knowsley, Merseyside, the
pupil-teacher ratio in secondary schools rose from 13.7 pupils per teacher
in 1989 to 16.4 in 1992, almost back to the 1978 figure of 16.7.
Other areas that have seen sharp increases include Newham, London, where the
ratio is up from 13.6 to 16.1 in the three years; South Tyneside, up from 14
to 16.1; North Tyneside, up from 13.8 to 15.5; Rochdale, up from 14 to 15.5;
and Walsall, West Midlands, up from 13.6 to 15.2.
Last week the education department highlighted findings in the annual Social
Trends survey of reduced class sizes as evidence of 'significant
improvements in education'. But this was based on national figures to 1991,
which showed a drop in the ratio from 17.8 to 15 since the 1970s.
Mr John Howson, deputy director of Oxford Brookes's school of education,
said: 'Restrictions on local authority spending seem to be the main cause of
the sharp deterioration.
'The local management of schools policy, under which budgets are devolved
from councils to head teachers, cannot put more teachers in the classroom if
grants do not keep pace with education inflation.'
It had been expected that local management would direct more education
resources into classroom teaching, but Mr Howson believes it may be
diverting resources into repairs, equipment and non-teaching posts such as
bursars.
The research shows a slower rate of deterioration in county district class
sizes. In the three years to 1992 the secondary-level pupils-to-teacher
ratio worsened by more than 0.5 in 14 county LEAs - the biggest rise being
1.2 in Derbyshire, a county with acute financial problems. In None saw an
improvement of more than 0.5.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
