<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Service sector 'new industrial dinosaur'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS, insurance companies, defence contractors and government departments
are taking over from textiles, shipbuilding, steel and coal as Britain's
industrial dinosaurs, says BWD Rensburg, the Huddersfield-based stockbroking
group, in its quarterly review of northern companies, published today.
Rising unemployment in southern England is the first sign of labour shakeout
and cost-cutting in the service sector similar to that which has devastated
smokestack industries in northern England during the last 15 years.
This has made old regional boundaries irrelevant when analysing unemployment
trends, says Mr John Dyson, BWD's corporate services director. Every region
now has successful areas and blackspots, he says.
Jobs in the north are less concentrated in single sectors and areas, and
there are now many more small businesses in the region and a wider spread of
companies. This, according to the review, is a result of the region having
to restructure after the old industries were run down in the early 1980s,
and has helped the north withstand the recession.
'The mass service-industry employers are the new potential dinosaurs of the
next century,' Mr Dyson says.
The analysis - based on last October's jobless figures - found a cluster of
areas, mainly in a coastal belt running from Suffolk to Devon, where
unemployment had risen by 2.2 percentage points or more year-on-year. The
analysis attributes this to the concentration of service-sector industries
in those areas.
By contrast, 13 travel-to-work areas with an unemployment rate of less than
5.3 per cent are mainly clustered in a belt running across northern England
from the Lake District to North Yorkshire. The seasonally adjusted jobless
rate was 10.1 per cent last October.
The analysis also shows two similar areas of low unemployment in Wales, two
in Scotland, and another cluster of three, based on east Cheshire and the
Derbyshire peak district.
Because the areas are where people with good incomes live or spend their
leisure time, Mr Dyson calls the large cluster of low unemployment the
northern playground and the coastal belt of rising joblessness the southern
playground.
'The north-south playing field is now much more even, with no clearly
winning regions emerging,' he says.
The Quarterly Review. BWD Rensburg, Woodsome House, Fenay Bridge,
Huddersfield HD8 0JG. Pounds 40 per copy or Pounds 120 per year.
</TEXT>
