<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / TUC urges Pounds 4bn crisis cash for jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government should implement a Pounds 4bn emergency work package to
create 200,000 new jobs and 500,000 training and work experience places, the
Trades Union Congress urges.
Its Budget submission, published today, says job insecurity and unemployment
are the most important barriers to a recovery in consumer confidence.
The TUC hints at a trade-off between pay restraint and job creation - a
controversial signal in view of the TUC's commitment to free collective
bargaining. It says that the government's limit of 1.5 per cent pay rises in
the public sector will not prevent substantial job losses. 'Instead the
government should engage the public-sector employers and unions in
discussions to sustain quality services while stabilising living standards
and employment,' the submission says.
Workfare - people being forced to work for unemployment benefit - is
rejected by the TUC but it wants reform of the benefit system to help people
back into jobs.
It proposes abolishing the 21-hour rule under which unemployed people are
refused benefit if they enter a training or education course that takes more
than 21 hours a week. Employees' National Insurance Contributions should be
increased by about 50p per week to finance temporary work programmes for the
long-term unemployed, says Full Employment UK, the independent policy
consultancy.
</TEXT>
