<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Gould raps Labour on economic policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR was urged yesterday by Mr Bryan Gould to adopt a more radical
economic policy and to stop echoing the government's analysis.
The former shadow cabinet member said in a scathing attack on the Labour
leadership that while its paper setting out Budget measures was excellent,
it was 'sinking without trace - as virtually all Labour's economic policies
sink without trace'. That was because no one believed they could be
implemented.
Speaking on BBC Television's On the Record, Mr Gould, who stood against Mr
John Smith for the party leadership and later resigned from the shadow
cabinet over European policy, also criticised the party for being too
cautious.
'It is time the Labour party showed the way and led the way by breaking free
from that last hangover of an imperial economy,' he said.
Mr Gould's words will fuel the argument in the party about its future
direction. His belief that Labour should have full employment as a core aim
of economic policy strikes a chord with some Labour spokesmen. He also
called for an increase in public spending, especially for infrastructure
investment.
</TEXT>
