<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Trident Dock Contest: Tense campaign waged with ferocity and
scare tactics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHATEVER THE outcome in the battle between Devonport and Rosyth, the
protests will be loud.
Rosyth royal dockyard is the biggest single industrial site in Scotland, and
Devonport the biggest in south-west England. Both areas suffer from high
unemployment and failure to win the nuclear contract, which would guarantee
jobs well into the next century, will shatter local morale.
Hence the ferocity of the political campaign that has been raging between
the dockyards for nearly two years. It is likely to be seen as a classic
political lobbying campaign, involving national defence, the future of the
Royal Navy, judgments on value for money and political expediency.
Scare tactics have also been used: Rosyth's management has dropped hints
about nuclear safety risks at Devonport; a study commissioned by Devonport
questioned the strategic and political wisdom of concentrating all nuclear
work in Scotland. In addition, a senior defence ministry civil servant has
faced allegations of bias; and both sides have complained that the goalposts
for tendering have been moved to their disadvantage.
A director of Devonport Management said: 'It is like being at war for the
last two years. It has dominated all our waking hours and involved all our
families.' The sentiment could equally have come from Rosyth. The yard there
has been building a special dock, known as RD57, since 1987 and was
initially the natural choice for a reduced submarine programme.
But Devonport Management realised that its future would be bleak, or
non-existent, without the nuclear contract. The question was how to go about
getting it, with Rosyth apparently home and dry. A series of brainstorming
sessions was held to decide how Devonport could do the work more cheaply.
The answer was to upgrade the docks at Devonport rather than build new ones.
Devonport sent its unsolicited proposal to the MoD and, crucially, to the
Treasury in April 1991. Both liked the proposals in principle, and a more
detailed analysis was completed by the following November.
The plan was for a Pounds 170m development over 10 years aimed at
undercutting the cost to the government of going ahead with Rosyth's Pounds
400m RD57 project. In addition to the two docks in Devonport's present
submarine complex, it planned to adapt three big dry docks designed before
the first world war to accommodate battleships.
Devonport said its scheme would save Pounds 250m on construction costs and
as much again in ship maintenance through economies of scale in refitting
over the rest of the decade.
It was a masterstroke that received the backing of the Navy, threw Rosyth
off balance, and immediately put Devonport in with a chance of victory on
cost grounds. The original MoD strategy of placing the contract with Rosyth
was dropped in favour of an open competition between the two yards. This was
when 'the great nuclear race' really started.
Rosyth recognised that if the MoD decided to cut the number of dockyards
from two to one, the survivor would almost certainly be Devonport. It
therefore had to persuade the MoD it should stick to a dual site plan for
refitting Trident and all other submarines at Rosyth and preserve Devonport
for surface ships. Its campaign had two strands.
First, to demonstrate to the MoD that a Trident operation at Rosyth would be
the most cost-effective. Second, to ensure that ministers and MPs realised
that if Rosyth did not win the Trident contract the yard would eventually
close, creating an economic catastrophe for Scotland and a political
disaster for the Conservative party, which has only 11 out of 72 Scottish
MPs.
Meanwhile Devonport, having scored with its technical campaign, launched a
parallel political campaign to gain wider support for winning the nuclear
contract. It was decided that outside help was needed, and a year ago the
Rowland Group, a Saatchi public relations company, was commissioned to lobby
the media and promote Devonport's case at Westminster and in Whitehall.
Similarly, Rosyth hired the Westminster consultants GJW to help put its
case, and made use of the fact that in Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary,
Scotland had a voice in cabinet and a force of civil servants in the
Scottish Office who could be relied on to support its case on regional
economic grounds.
Devonport has been well aware of its relative lack of political clout
nationally but it has been supported vigorously by the Labour-led Plymouth
City Council, local unions, and the Conservative-led Devon and Cornwall
county councils.
Rosyth argues that the dice have been loaded consistently against its bid.
It maintains that Devonport was 'invited out of the blue' to submit its
initial bid for the Trident contract, while the MoD was urging Rosyth to
concentrate on improving the RD57 scheme instead of considering a cheaper
upgrade option.
In response to Devonport's Pounds 170m upgraded scheme, Rosyth last June cut
the cost of RD57 from Pounds 400m to Pounds 267m by abandoning the plan to
put the whole facility under cover.
Then in December, when the cost of Devonport's project had been pared to
Pounds 130m, Rosyth submitted yet another plan. It would be prepared to drop
its new-build scheme and, like Devonport, convert existing docks to take
Trident at a cost of Pounds 147m. It was told on January 14 that the scheme
had been rejected.
It was then that Rosyth decided to make a last bid to save the contract. Mr
Allan Smith, Rosyth managing director, contacted Mr Lang and Mr Malcolm
Rifkind, defence secretary, and met the Scottish media. The protests worked,
and on January 18 Downing Street announced that the period of consultation
would be extended.
</TEXT>
<XX>
