<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Trident Dock Contest: Closure threatens thousands of jobs -
Gillian Tett assesses the mood among businesses in two communities waiting
for the long-feared bombshell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF Rosyth or Devonport closes, the thousands of dockworkers will not be the
only people to lose their jobs. Almost 30,000 jobs in the Devon and Cornwall
area depend directly or indirectly on the Devonport complex, with up to 600
local companies drawing business from the yard, says Mr Paul Bishop, a
lecturer at Plymouth University.
The picture is similar at at Rosyth, where a recent study by Fife Regional
Council claims that at least 800 businesses in Scotland have dealings with
the yard. Few doubt that the closure of either yard would trigger knock-on
job losses across each region's economy.
Mr Malcolm Haggart, managing director of a Plymouth marine engineering
company, said: 'If Devonport loses, it would be like dropping an atomic bomb
on the shopping centre. It would devastate Plymouth.'
Uncertainty about the yards' future has prompted many local suppliers to
diversify in recent years. Although the larger defence suppliers have been
hit by wider defence cuts, most insist that their businesses will not be
affected by the eventual location of the sole refitting yard.
Most of Devonport's specialist defence suppliers, for example, are already
located far outside the region.
Nevertheless, the businesses now at risk are the hordes of tiny enterprises
scattered around Rosyth and Plymouth which have grown around the rich
pickings of the yard. In Plymouth alone, for example, the Devonport complex
is estimated to generate some Pounds 521m of income for the region. And Mr
James Brodie, chief executive of Fife Chamber of Commerce, said: 'It could
have a devastating effect on the retail sector.'
Mr Bill Taylor, director of economic planning at Fife Regional Council,
said: 'The issue is not just about the direct suppliers but a chain of
suppliers.'
ROSYTH
Clark Retail
Newsagent
8 employees
Turnover Pounds 400,000Hundreds of local shops depend on the dockyard for
custom. 'If Rosyth goes it would put paid to a lot of our jobs,' says Mrs
Marilyn Sallnow, temporary manager of the Rosyth branch of Clark Retail, a
newsagent chain. It estimates that around 40 per cent of its business would
be lost. 'Rosyth would be like a ghost town,' adds Mrs Sallnow, whose
husband, father and brother-in-law all work at the yard.
Norman Davidson
Self-employed taxi driver
Rosyth's isolated location, several miles from the nearest big town, has
provided jobs for hundreds of taxi drivers.  'If the yard goes, it would
kill the taxi trade,' says Mr Norman Davidson, who believes that '20 per
cent of taxi drivers would go to the wall'.
Systems Reliability, Fife
44 employees
Turnover Pounds 4m
If Rosyth closes, local observers fear that it could lead to a drainage of
high-tech skills from the area. Small businesses such as Systems
Reliability, a local computer hardware and installation company, have grown
up around the yard and its suppliers. 'Our success is in local hands,' says
Mr Robert Rob, sales director.
Arco East Scotland, Linlithgow
85 employees
Turnover Pounds 10m
Arco East Scotland supplies protective clothing and safety equipment for the
yard workers - in the last three months it sold more than Pounds 60,000
worth of jackets alone to the dockyard.  'If Rosyth goes we would have to
set about laying people off, no question,' says Mr Ron Dow, divisional
director. Although Arco also supplies a wide range of other industrial
outlets, many of these are also linked to the yard. 'We supply so many of
the subcontractors - electrical shops, ship blasters, even bus companies.'
Wilkie Hook, Bowness
400-500 employees
Turnover Pounds 1m
The family business employs 150 men on contract ship-blasting at Rosyth. If
the ship and submarine refitting business disappears, it will have to lay
off almost all these workers. 'Many of those men won't be prepared to travel
to other parts of Scotland for work,' says Mr Archie Wilkie, director.
G and D Scaffolding Services,
Dunfermline
20 employees
Turnover Pounds 750,000
Although most suppliers have tried to diversify, many remain vulnerable
because of their small size. The privately owned G and D Scaffolding draws
25 per cent of its business from the yard.  'That means that we are not
totally dependent,' says Mr Gordon Hendry, G and D's owner. 'But you only
need to have a few other clients going down and the ratio changes.'
MacTaggart Scott, Edinburgh
350 employees
Turnover Pounds 12m
Although a number of specialised defence companies are located in Scotland,
many say their business could follow the refitting programme to Plymouth if
necessary. MacTaggart Scott, which produces hydraulic equipment for ships
and submarines, supplies both Rosyth and Devonport. 'I think both should be
kept open,' says Mr Patrick Prenter, managing director. Although only Pounds
500,00 of its business is directly linked to Rosyth, he admits that the
closure would mean 'the loss of jobs, albeit a limited number'.
Scottish Power, Glasgow
Turnover Pounds 635m
Fife Regional Council, Rosyth provides Pounds 24m of business for the energy
sector each year, supporting an estimated 310 jobs in electricity and gas.
Scottish Power, which supplies Rosyth, denies that losing the yard would
affect its overall financial performance.
GEC-Marconi simulation plant
400 employees in Fife
Turnover Pounds 50m
(7,000 to 8,000 employees throughout Scotland
Turnover Pounds 400m)
GEC-Marconi, which has indicated it would be interested in bidding for
Rosyth or Devonport, produces specialised defence supplies for both yards
from factories across Britain. Its plant in Fife has provided simulation
equipment for Trident submarines.  Like other specialised defence suppliers
it insists the decision will not affect jobs.
DEVONPORT
Ron Dewdney
Cornish pasty business
32 employees
Turnover Pounds 700,000
Many local caterers and food shops depend on Devonport for their business.
The catering company Ron Dewdney, for example, sells about 2,000 Cornish
pasties daily - a quarter of its production - directly to ships and yard
workers, with several thousand more sold to the yard's suppliers. If the
yard closed Mr Alan Meatyard, manager, would make at least five employees
redundant. 'It's the knock-on effect that's the real problem,' he says. 'A
lot of the people I supply with pasties supply the yard.'
Osmond Guest House
Turnover Pounds 24,000
More than 150 family-run guest houses depend on the yard for their
livelihood. Mr Mike Richards, owner of the guest house, explains: 'During
the week we get contract workers from firms like Marconi staying here. At
the weekend we get sailors.'
Avondale Arms
Pub
5 employees
Pubs fear the loss of spending power resulting from Devonport closing would
hit them particularly hard. Mr Arthur Squire, who has run the Avondale Arms
next to the yard for the past 43 years, says: 'My trade is the yard. If that
goes, I go.'
Owens Uniforms
30 employees
Turnover Pounds 500,000
Mr Clive Owens, managing director, has been making uniforms for the Royal
Navy for 50 years. Eighty per cent of his orders come from the Ministry of
Defence, with 100 uniforms going directly to Devonport each year. Although
Mr Owens believes that the jobs at his company will be safe even if
Devonport loses the bid, the impact of such an outcome would be
'devastating' for the area. 'It's the uncertainty that is the worst,' he
says.
Fox and Haggart
Marine engineers
18 employees
Turnover Pounds 250,000
A huge network of tiny businesses, often family-run, has grown up to supply
Devonport. Fox and Haggart has depended on the yard over three generations.
Mr Malcolm Haggart hopes to hand the business on to his young sons. But if
Devonport loses the contract he will have to 'seriously consider' closing
down. 'Some of the people working here have been here for 40 years,' he
says. 'It's all they know. How can you expect them to retrain or get another
job?'
Bee-Clear
Industrial ship cleaners
94 employees
If the yard were to close it would not just be the yard's suppliers that
would be hit, but the suppliers' suppliers too, says Mr Keith Rickard,
managing director of Bee-Clear. The company itself would cut 60 jobs.
South West Crane Hire, Exeter
44 employees
Turnover Pounds 2m
The Devonport yard provides business for construction companies across the
south-west. But if Devonport loses the bid South West Crane Hire would shed
a third of its workforce. 'I've got no alternative,' says Mr Michael
Jeffery, managing director.
South West Water, Exeter
Water suppliers
About 2,000 employees
Turnover Pounds 96.7m
Devonport's contract with South West Water represents one of its most
significant local contracts in financial terms, according to Mr Paul Bishop
of Plymouth University. South West Water denies that losing Devonport would
lead to redundancies. Yet Mr Bill Frazer, South West Water's managing
director, has added his voice to the political lobbying. In a recent letter
to Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, he declared that 'DML is one of
our largest customers, and makes an important contribution to the costs of
our huge Pounds 4m per week investment in improving treatment works, water
mains and sew-ers'.
British Aerospace
1,000 employees
British Aerospace, a supplier to Devonport, relocated to Plymouth to be near
the naval docks. Like most specialist defence suppliers the company insists
that if the naval work moved its business would follow it. 'But it would
make the task of distribution to our customers much more difficult and
expensive,' says Mr Chris Tear, head of public affairs.
</TEXT>
