<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Trident Dock Contest: Work for non-MoD organisations to
account for 40 per cent of activity in 1992-93 at Rosyth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT THE Rosyth yard, work for organisations other than the Ministry of
Defence will account for nearly 40 per cent of activity in 1992-93 and 20
per cent of its expected turnover of Pounds 165m, Richard Evans and James
Buxton write. The gap is due to the high-value nature of much of the MoD
work. Some 800 of the yard's 4,100 employees are permanently engaged in
non-MoD activities.
Diversification began soon after Babcock Thorn took over. Mr Allan
Macpherson, now director of manufacturing, wanted to market the high level
of skills in the dockyard and initially exploited the craftsmanship of the
cabinetmakers whose main job had been fitting out cabins on warships. That
led to the creation of a furniture and joinery business which now supplies
furniture for the retail and the timeshare markets.
At Devonport dockyard, 23 per cent of turnover last year came from contracts
won through competitive tender, half of that on work unrelated to defence.
It included yacht building and refitting, and engine servicing for British
Rail. A contract has just been won to build specialist trailers to transport
Russian nuclear warheads for dismantling.
The main targets being sought in the Plymouth area are high-tech and light
engineering groups. Companies that have moved to the area in recent years
are Toshiba, the television manufacturer; Murata, the Japanese-owned
producer of ceramic capacitators; and Wrigley, the US-owned chewing gum
producer.
</TEXT>
