<PROFILE>_AN-DBACCAATFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Devaluation of the Punt: Government awaits the political
counterpunch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRISH industry and farm leaders at the weekend expressed relief at the
government's defeat in its battle to defend the punt. But the reversal is
likely to lead to some tough political battles ahead.
Mr Michael Noonan, finance spokesman for the opposition Fine Gael party,
described the decision to devalue as 'an ignominious climbdown and a most
dismal defeat for the government. They failed to put domestic policies in
place that would convince the international community that we were serious
about the defence of the currency and they also failed to convince our
colleagues in Europe that they should come to our aid.'
The resolve of Mr Bertie Ahern, the finance minister, was finally broken by
the loss of political and business consensus at home and the threat of a
sharp increase next week in mortgage and bank lending rates. He said
yesterday: 'I could not put my hand on my heart and recommend to the
government that Irish mortgage holders and business should pay another 3, 4
or 5 per cent (on interest rates) for the sake of trying to win a battle for
a European system where I was not getting even equal support that the French
were getting.'
Since the last of Ireland's exchange controls were lifted at the beginning
of the year, interest rate management has been the government's main weapon
to defend the punt. This has forced up commercial lending rates to record
levels. Several key manufacturing associations, particularly in the
textiles, food processing and engineering sectors, warned last week that
thousands of job losses were in the pipeline, and urged the government to
devalue. Farm leaders have been recommending a devaluation for months.
Although the immediate threat of big job losses and more interest rate rises
has been averted by the devaluation, it is thought unlikely that commercial
lending rates will fall from their current levels for some time yet. As a
result of staying within the narrow band of the ERM, downward movements in
Irish rates will still have to await cuts in German rates if further attacks
on the punt are to be avoided.
There is also lingering concern about whether the markets will see a 10 per
cent devaluation as sufficient, especially if the UK pursues an aggressive
interest rate policy.
Mr John Beggs, chief economist at Allied Irish Banks, said: 'In the short
term I would expect some improvement on the interest rate front. Looking
beyond that, I think we have hitched our wagon to sterling and whether you
agree with the devaluation policy or not, that is a problem we face.'
Mr Ahern defended his no-devaluation stance. 'If we had given in last
September we could well be here today on the third or fourth devaluation.'
He said there would be no further devaluations. 'We have built into the
figures competitive advantage for future turbulence and we have done that to
convince the markets that that is the end of speculation.'
The country's priority now was to diversify further its exports away from
the UK market.
The immediate cost to the government of the devaluation has been to increase
the foreign debt by IPounds 1bn and its servicing charge by IPounds 80m per
year. The new Fianna Fail-Labour coalition has committed itself to a job
creation and public sector investment programme, which will entail a public
sector deficit in the region of 3.2 per cent of GDP this year, and there is
still some IPounds 300m in commitments whose financing has not yet been
resolved.
Mr Ahern promised yesterday that next month's budget would be a tough one,
as any softening on that front would again encourage the speculators. This
is likely to produce tensions within the ruling coalition, as Labour views
job creation as a priority and will resist cuts in its favoured investment
programmes.
The Irish Congress of Trade Unions, which supported the no-devaluation
policy, also hinted yesterday that its policy of negotiated pay restraint
over the past six years might now be reviewed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IEZ  Ireland, EC.
</CN>
