<PROFILE>_AN-DBACCAARFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / Ministries blamed over red tape
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INCREASING burden of red tape on British business is partly caused by
the ambivalence of the Department of Trade and Industry and the Treasury
towards deregulation, according to a paper published today by the Social
Market Foundation.
The paper is written by Mr David Willetts, Conservative MP for Havant, who
was formerly a Downing Street policy adviser and director of the Centre for
Policy Studies, the think tank founded by Lady Thatcher and Lord Joseph. It
is published a day before a seminar called by Mr John Major at which
ministers and senior civil servants will be expected to explain their plans
for deregulation.
Mr Willetts says red tape has increased steadily since the mid-1980s and now
represents a serious obstacle to the creation of a flexible, dynamic
economy. An important reason for the growth in regulation is the ambivalence
of the two main ministries involved, he suggests.
The DTI was concerned mainly with large companies, which often regarded
regulation as a useful barrier to new competition. The Treasury saw
regulation as a way of attaining objectives without public spending.
Mr Willetts targets 10 areas of government legislation for urgent action,
including the Companies Act requirement that small firms carry out an audit,
the quality management standard BS5750, food safety legislation and the
Children Act, governing child care facilities.
Regulation is allowed to proliferate because departments aim for the highest
standards without questioning the cost; because central government wrongly
blames Europe or local authorities for the problem; and because in areas
such as safety, regulation appeals to our emotions.
The government needs to look at a stronger lay involvement in working groups
drafting legislation so that acceptable basic standards are adopted, Mr
Willetts said. Business should be disciplined by the prospect of legal
liability rather than be forced to comply with a mass of regulation designed
to prevent mishaps.
Areas of action should include:
Removing the statutory audit for small firms. This can cost up to 4 per cent
of turnover and it prevents companies using low-cost book-keepers. The EC
directive harmonising company law does not require an independent audit but
the UK insists on one.
The Food Safety Act. This was introduced after food poisoning scares and
imposes tight controls on retailers. Yet there is evidence that, in many
instances, problems arise further down the food chain.
Rail and Tube safety. Recent accidents have prompted a huge programme of
safety spending, pushing up fares. Yet rail remains one of the safest forms
of transport. Accident inquiries often produce uncosted and overlapping
proposals for reform.
Deregulation. Social Market Foundation, 20 Queen Anne's Gate, London SW1H
9AA. Pounds 3.
Small companies 'more confident', Page 9
</TEXT>
<XX>
