<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 93 / ICI plans 14.5% rises for flexible working
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPERIAL Chemical Industries' 20,000 manual workers look likely to receive
pay rises of at least 14.5 per cent during their current 12-month wage round
ending in June.
This compares with private-sector increases averaging just over 3 per cent.
The government wants to impose a 1.5 per cent pay limit in the public
sector.
ICI insists that the increases being negotiated at local level are
self-financing and the price is worth paying because it involves sweeping
changes in working practices.
So far 3,000 workers at the company's sites at Grangemouth, Huddersfield and
Yalding in Kent have received 6 per cent wage increases as a result of
workplace reforms that involve greater worker flexibility and
'multi-skilling'.
These rises are in addition to 5.1 per cent which ICI manual workers
received last June through the company's normal annual pay negotiations and
3.5 per cent awarded the following month from the company's employee profit
scheme.
Shift and other allowances as well as call-out payments are also being
increased by 6 per cent under the local deals.
As a result, the annual salaries of ICI manual workers will now range
between Pounds 10,734 and Pounds 16,011.
Two further increases of 4 per cent each will be awarded on the first and
second anniversaries of the deals.
The company said it expected the rest of its manual workforce to agree
workplace changes at local level over the next few months. All will receive
the same pay increases as a result.
ICI says the local pay deals derive from a 1991 agreement signed with the
five unions recognised by the company, which radically reformed work
organisation across the company's 13 plants. It has taken more than 18
months of intensive local negotiation for the workplace changes to be
agreed.
