<PROFILE>_AN-DA4ASACXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 93 / Russia to build new gas pipes for German market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GAZPROM, Russia's state gas production company, is building two new gas
pipelines to Germany in an effort to avoid disruption of gas supplies
running through Ukraine, Mr Rem Vyakhirev, the company's chairman, said.
There was an outcry in Germany in October when the pressure in the gas
pipeline, which supplies 31 per cent of German demand, dropped for days as
supplies through Ukraine were disrupted.
Mr Vyakhirev said the interruption in supplies in October was caused by a
technical problem that could 'easily be corrected'.
'Of course, consumers must be guaranteed a stable supply of gas, but we have
taken a lot of steps to avoid any repetition of the disruption.'
The pipeline is due to be finished within two to three years.
However, it is widely believed that the gas supply problem in October was
caused by Ukraine stealing gas from the export pipeline after its own
supplies were interrupted.
German diplomats are believed to have stressed the seriousness of the
situation to the governments of Ukraine and Russia.
Mr Vyakhirev said gas flowing through the existing pipeline had a time lag
of five to seven days, so it could take a week to sort out any problems. The
new pipelines will have a three-day time lag so disruptions could be
corrected much quickly, he said. He would not disclose the cost of the
pipelines, but it is believed to represent an investment of Dollars 1bn
(Pounds 600m).
Construction of the new pipelines has already begun in Russia with
completion of the first pipeline to Germany due in 1997. The company is
expected to run one line through the Baltic states and Poland, entering
Germany at Frankfurt an der Oder.
Mr Vyakhirev said a final decision on the pipelines' routes will be taken
later this year.
Gazprom is expecting to sell around 8bn cubic metres a year to Poland en
route, which will leave an additional 32bn cubic metres a year for Germany.
Mr Vyakhirev would not disclose the cost of the lines.
Gazprom has agreed a Dollars 50m contract with Compressor Controls, the US
gas supplies company, for the supply of control equipment that will improve
the efficiency of the company's pipelines and gas processing stations.
The contract runs over seven years and the company estimates it will save
10bn to 15bn cubic metres of gas a year that would have been lost by
inefficient processing.
</TEXT>
