<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 93 / Row over T-shirt design set for High Court hearing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHILE rows over copyright in the fashion industry are common, disputes are
usually settled out of court. But changes to the legal aid system may make
it harder for small designers to fight their corner in the manner of Antoni
&amp; Alison, the London fashion house.
Antoni &amp; Alison was supported by legal aid at a preliminary hearing this
week in the High Court. It is claiming copyright infringement over a T-shirt
produced by Giorgio Armani, the Italian fashion house.
Armani has withdrawn the disputed design in the UK and ceased using it in
advertising, but Antoni &amp; Alison is seeking a High Court ruling to prevent
it being sold or used overseas. The High Court agreed to hear Antoni &amp;
Alison's allegation that Armani has infringed its copyright. The case will
probably be heard in September.
Lawyers estimate that the case will cost each side about Pounds 50,000.
Armani's global annual turnover is thought to exceed Pounds 300m while
Antoni &amp; Alison's sales were less than Pounds 250,000 last year.
Armani has declined to comment on any aspect of the case.
Mr Achilleas Constantinou, head of the Fashion Designers Protection
Association, says he sees about 100 cases of alleged copyright infringement
every year. However, he says 99.9 per cent of cases are settled out of court
'because in a genuine case of copyright infringement one side is lying. What
happens is that the bigger party often uses expensive legal muscle to
frighten the potential plaintiff into dropping the action.'
Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, has proposed that the level of disposable
income at which an applicant is entitled to free legal aid be reduced from
Pounds 3,060 per annum to Pounds 2,213 per annum from April. The Law
Society, the solicitors' governing body in England and Wales, says this
would remove 7m people from eligibility.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P23  Apparel and Other Textile Products.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Patents.
    GOVT  Legal issues.
