<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 93 / MPs give Soley bill on press second reading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRIVATE member's bill introduced by Labour MP Mr Clive Soley which seeks
to establish an independent press authority for newspapers and periodicals
was given a second reading by 119 votes to 15 in the Commons yesterday.
The bill, which aims to secure 'due accuracy', has only a remote chance of
reaching the statute book because of the number and scope of amendments that
have to be considered during the line-by-line committee stage.
In response to questions at a press conference Mr Soley, MP for Hammersmith,
warned newspaper editors that unless they co-operated in getting 'something
like my bill' on the statute book they risked legislation on privacy without
any counter-balancing measure on press freedom.
Mr Soley also underlined his willingness to accept amendments supporting
press freedom.
The bill was described as 'premature and misconceived' by Mr Robert Key, the
junior heritage minister.
He nevertheless reaffirmed the government's dissatisfaction with the
existing Press Complaints Commission. Mr Key made clear that ministerial
reluctance to establish a statutory regulatory body, as recommended by Sir
David Calcutt in his recent report, did not mean that it had been ruled out.
The government will take into account press response to Sir David's
criticisms and the views expressed in the debate on the bill and in the
forthcoming report by the Commons heritage committee on privacy and media
intrusion before reaching conclusions about a statutory regulatory body.
Earlier Mr John Major, the prime minister, said his decision to issue writs
for libel against two magazines concerning reports about his private life
had not affected his decision not to support the bill.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651  Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P2711  Newspapers.
</IN>
<XX>
