<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 93 / Clinton acts on gays in military
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday announced a compromise approach to the
controversial issue of ending the 50-year ban on homosexuals serving in the
US military.
He announced that the military would immediately stop screening recruits for
sexual orientation. He directed Mr Les Aspin, secretary of defence, to
prepare by July 15 an executive order ending the proscription on homosexual
service but including a strict new code of conduct covering sexual
behaviour. Meanwhile, all legal actions seeking the discharge of gays from
the armed services are to be suspended.
Also in the interim, Congress will hold its own hearings on the issue.
Senator Sam Nunn from Georgia, Democratic chairman of the armed service
committee and the most potent congressional critic of Mr Clinton's
initiative, said that he was satisfied with this approach, the essence of
which was hammered out by the president and himself, along with Senator
George Mitchell, the Democratic leader, in the White House on Thursday
night.
Mr Clinton's hand had been temporarily strengthened on Thursday when a
federal judge in California declared the ban unconstitutional. However his
ruling only applied to the parts of the state in his jurisdiction.
Making the announcement in person at the White House, the president
emphasised again that he was standing on principle. 'I believe that American
citizens who want to serve their country should be able to do so unless
their conduct disqualifies them from doing so,' he said.
But he conceded that 'military life is fundamentally different' and might
well impose 'necessary restrictions on behaviour, many of which would be
intolerable in civilian society.'
This is a clear invitation to Mr Nunn and the chiefs of staff under General
Colin Powell to revise the military code of conduct so as to meet some, if
not all, of their fundamental objections to admitting homosexuals. These
have centred on the implied threats to morale, efficiency and privacy.
'I agree with the joint chiefs that the highest standards of conduct must be
required,' Mr Clinton said. 'This cannot be accomplished overnight.'
Some Republicans continued yesterday to threaten to frustrate the
president's initiative, the fulfilment of a campaign promise as well as a
question of principle. But Sen Mitchell was confident he had the votes to
stop any legislative trickery and Mr Clinton urged the opposition not to
'play politics' by tagging amendments on to the family leave bill.
Mr Clinton said he hoped the agreed approach would now leave his new
administration free to concentrate on his promised economic reforms.
</TEXT>
