<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 93 / Deadline set for Bosnia peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIA'S three warring factions will be asked by mediators today for a final
decision on an internationally-brokered peace plan, in spite of the fact
that Bosnian Moslems oppose many of its provisions.
The co-chairmen of the Geneva peace conference, Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord
Owen, have made clear that they are not prepared to extend the negotiations
indefinitely and that they will give the three Bosnian groups one more
chance to say 'yes' or 'no' at face-to-face talks today.
Failing a favourable reply to their proposals, which include a
constitutional framework, a map of the 10 provinces into which Bosnia will
be divided and ceasefire arrangements, the mediators have said they would
ask the UN Security Council to impose a settlement.
Lord Owen said yesterday he was confident 'at the end of the day' an
agreement would be reached. 'We may not reach it totally here (in Geneva),
but if not, we'll reach it in New York.'
Lord Owen said he and Mr Vance would report to the UN Security Council after
today's meeting and might press for sanctions against any side blocking the
accord.
Mr Haris Silajdzic, the Bosnian Moslem foreign minister, poured cold water
on hopes an overall agreement might be reached today, following progress
made towards agreement on transitional arrangements for the administration
of Bosnia between application of a ceasefire and implementation of a new
constitution.
Under the interim arrangements, a nine-member body composed of three
representatives from each ethnic group would take over from Bosnia's elected
presidency after a ceasefire.
Mr Silajdzic said his government could not accept either the Vance-Owen
package because the Moslems considered it would lead to the ethnic division
of the country and was tantamount to rewarding Serb aggression. 'We, as a
member of the UN will never accept the abolition of our constitution, our
legality, which is based on free and democratic elections,' he said.
Yesterday ambassador Muhamed Sacirbey of Bosnia wrote to the UN calling for
an emergency meeting of the Security Council to deal with 'gross
manifestations of renewed Serbian and Montenegrin aggression.'
The Bosnian Croats are the only ones who have so far accepted the Vance-Owen
package. It was not certain last night whether the Bosnian Moslems or Serbs
would bow to pressure by the mediators.
</TEXT>
