<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Economic data fail to give
spur to Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices moved in a narrow range yesterday as investors struggled to
find interest in stocks in spite of some further good economic data, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 3.78 at 3,31 .03. The
more broadly based Standard&amp;Poor's 500 ended 0.15 firmer at 438.81, while
the Amex composite finished 0.59 higher at 411.08, and the Nasdaq composite
closed up 1.67 at 696.34. Trading volume on the NYSE was 248m shares, and
rises outnumbered declines by 1000 to 805.
The day's economic news should have been positive for the market. New
factory orders for durable goods, a notoriously volatile and unreliable
indicator, surged 9.1 per cent in December, the largest monthly gain in more
than a year. Other data showed that personal income rose by 1.0 per cent and
personal spending climbed 0.5 per cent last month, both solid increases.
Although the figures were all stronger than analysts had expected, they were
not enough to encourage much buying of stocks. Investors, it seemed, had
decided to take their cue from the bond market, which fell during the
morning on the data. Although bond prices later recovered, investor
enthusiasm for stocks remained muted.
Among individual stocks, Xerox jumped Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars 85 3/4 in
spite of news of a Dollars 736m net loss in the final quarter of last year,
compared with a profit of Dollars 91m a year earlier. The shares held up
well because earnings were affected by special one off charges, and because
the company issued positive statements about the outlook for this year.
Pfizer eased Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 65 in busy trading after broking house
PaineWebber downgraded its investment rating on the stock due to
uncertainties surrounding a class-action lawsuit that might be filed against
the company alleging that a unit of Pfizer manufactured defective artificial
hips.
Airline stocks rebounded from news earlier in the week of bad fourth quarter
earnings. Delta rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 51 7/8 , AMR, parent of
American Airlines, put on Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 63 1/8 , and UAL climbed
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 123 1/2 .
Cellular telephone companies remained under heavy pressure over speculation
that use of the telephones causes health problems. Motorola slumped Dollars
4 7/8 to Dollars 51, and on the Nasdaq market, McCaw Cellular dropped
Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars 32 1/2 and LIN Broadcasting fell Dollars 3 3/4 to
Dollars 78 1/4 .
Canada
TORONTO SHARE prices ended the week little changed in active trading.
According to preliminary data, the 300 composite lost 2.45 points, or 0.0
per cent, closing at 3,305.47. Advancing issues led declines 352 to 265,
volume fell to 40.73m shares from 46.16m shares yesterday, and trading value
was CDollars 363.9m compared with CDollars 458.4m.
Northern Telecom fell 2 1/4 to 54 7/8 . The company said its president and
chief operating officer, Jean Monty, will replace
